T*
(Agentic Engineering Patterns > The defining characteristic of a coding agent is that it can) Tj
T*
(execute the code that it writes. This is what makes coding agents so much more useful than LLMs) Tj
T*
(that simply spit out code without any way to verify it. Never assume that code generated by an) Tj
T*
(LLM works until that code has been executed. Coding agents have the ability to confirm that the) Tj
T*
(code they have produced works as intended, or iterate further on that code until it does.) Tj
T*
(Getting agents to write unit tests , especially using test-first TDD, is a powerful way to) Tj
T*
(ensure they have exercised the code they are writing. That's not the only worthwhile approach,) Tj
T*
(though. Just because code passes tests doesn't mean it works as intended. Anyone who's worked) Tj
T*
(with automated tests will have seen cases where the tests all pass but the code itself fails in) Tj
T*
(some obvious way - it might crash the server on startup, fail to display a crucial UI element,) Tj
T*
(or miss some detail that the tests failed to cover. Automated tests are no replacement for) Tj
T*
(manual testing . I like to see a feature working with my own eye before I land it in a release.) Tj
T*
(I've found that getting agents to manually test code is valuable as well...) Tj
